          </div>

          <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold text-slate-900 mt-8 mb-4">Palmer (Median Age: 38 Years)</h3>

          <p>
            Palmer is a mid-1980s to 1990s subdivision on the lower plain at 88-95 meters elevation, bounded roughly by Lakeshore Road, Guelph Line, New Street, and Brant Street. With a 38-year median age, Palmer represents Burlington's first generation of homes built under modern building codes with foundation waterproofing requirements. Most homes have functional weeping tile systems, but 30+ years of service means many are approaching the end of their effective lifespan.
          </p>

          <p>
            Palmer's challenge is Spencer Creek influence on its eastern edge. Properties east of Elizabeth Street and south of New Street sit within 200-400 meters of the creek, experiencing elevated water tables during spring snowmelt and summer storm events. These homes show basement seepage patterns that correlate with creek flows rather than local rainfall, indicating groundwater infiltration from creek recharge.
          </p>

          <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold text-slate-900 mt-8 mb-4">Orchard (Median Age: 41 Years)</h3>

          <p>
            Orchard sits at 95-110 meters elevation between Brant Street and Walkers Line, north of New Street. Built primarily in the 1980s, the neighborhood benefits from modern construction standards and good natural drainage on the lower plain. Waterproofing issues here typically result from poor maintenance (clogged gutters, blocked downspouts) rather than systemic foundation problems.
          </p>

          <p>
            However, Orchard's mature landscaping and extensive use of finished basements mean waterproofing projects often involve additional costs for landscaping restoration and interior drywall/flooring removal to access foundation walls from the interior. Budget an additional 15-25% beyond base waterproofing costs for these ancillary expenses.
          </p>

          <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold text-slate-900 mt-8 mb-4">Headon Forest (Median Age: 33 Years)</h3>

          <p>
            Headon Forest is a 1990s development on the escarpment between 180-210 meters elevation, west of Walkers Line and north of Upper Middle Road. Despite being Burlington's newest area covered in this analysis, Headon Forest presents some of the city's most challenging waterproofing conditions due to its position on and near the escarpment face where limestone bedrock lies at or near surface.
          </p>

          <p>
            Properties throughout Headon Forest encounter bedrock during excavation, with many sitting directly on limestone with just 0.5-1.5 meters of overburden soil. Groundwater flows through bedrock fractures and bedding planes, creating conditions where water appears at foundation walls under pressure even when surface soils are dry. Spring snowmelt regularly pushes water through these bedrock pathways, causing basement seepage in homes that show no issues from summer through fall.
          </p>

          <p>
            Waterproofing in Headon Forest requires escarpment-specific approaches: deep drainage to intercept bedrock water, full-height rubberized membranes, and often sub-slab drainage systems to handle water moving upward through floor slabs. Costs here run $200-$265 per linear foot, and projects routinely encounter flowing water during excavation that requires temporary pumping to complete the work.
          </p>

          <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold text-slate-900 mt-8 mb-4">Roseland (Median Age: 29 Years)</h3>

          <p>
            Roseland is Burlington's youngest neighborhood in this analysis, developed primarily 1995-2005 on the lower plain at 85-92 meters elevation near Spencer Creek and LaSalle Park. Modern building code compliance means most homes have functional waterproofing systems, but the neighborhood's youth doesn't eliminate water issues—just changes their nature.
          </p>

          <p>
            Roseland properties close to Spencer Creek face the same creek-influenced water table issues as older Palmer and Aldershot homes, but with one advantage: their drainage systems are 40-50 years newer and generally still functional. Waterproofing work in Roseland typically involves supplementing existing systems—adding sump pumps, installing backwater valves, improving grading—rather than complete system replacement required in older neighborhoods.
          </p>

          <p>
            The neighborhood's proximity to Lake Ontario and low elevation means properties here see high water tables (1-2 meters below basement floors) and benefit from dehumidification systems to manage humidity even when waterproofing keeps liquid water out. A 50-70 pint dehumidifier ($300-$500) is a worthwhile investment for Roseland basements.
          </p>
        </div>
