      <!-- Section 7: Permits & Compliance -->
      <section id="permits-compliance" class="mb-16 scroll-mt-8">
        <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-slate-900 mb-6 border-b-4 border-cyan-500 pb-2">
          7. Conservation Halton Compliance & Halton Region Programs
        </h2>

        <div class="prose prose-lg max-w-none text-slate-700 space-y-6">
          <p>
            Basement waterproofing in Burlington requires navigating a multi-layered regulatory framework involving the City of Burlington, Conservation Halton, and Halton Region. Understanding which permits apply to your property and what financial assistance programs are available can save thousands of dollars and prevent project delays or enforcement issues.
          </p>

          <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold text-slate-900 mt-8 mb-4">City of Burlington Building Permits</h3>

          <p>
            Most Burlington waterproofing projects require building permits from the City's Building Department. Permit requirements apply when work involves: excavation below the frost line (1.2 meters in Burlington's climate zone), structural changes to foundation walls, installation or relocation of sump pumps with electrical connections, alterations to foundation drainage that discharge to municipal systems, and interior renovations exceeding $1,000 value that involve opening walls or floors.
          </p>

          <p>
            Burlington building permit fees for waterproofing typically range from $280 to $650 based on project value. A $15,000 exterior waterproofing project pays approximately $425 in permit fees. The permit application process takes 3-4 weeks for routine residential waterproofing, though complex projects or properties in regulated areas may require 5-7 weeks.
          </p>

          <p>
            Contractors typically handle permit applications as part of their service, but homeowners remain ultimately responsible for ensuring permits are obtained. Unpermitted waterproofing work creates problems during home sales when buyers' lawyers request building permit records, and can result in City enforcement orders requiring removal and re-inspection of work done without permits.
          </p>

          <div class="bg-white border border-slate-200 rounded-lg p-6 my-8 shadow-sm">
            <h3 class="font-bold text-xl text-slate-900 mb-4">Burlington Waterproofing Permit Requirements Quick Reference</h3>
            <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
              <div>
                <h4 class="font-semibold text-slate-900 mb-2">Requires City Building Permit</h4>
                <ul class="space-y-1 text-slate-700 text-sm list-disc list-inside">
                  <li>Exterior excavation and drainage installation</li>
                  <li>Foundation wall repairs or modifications</li>
                  <li>Sump pump installation with electrical work</li>
                  <li>Interior drainage with concrete floor work</li>
                  <li>Structural foundation repairs</li>
                </ul>
              </div>
              <div>
                <h4 class="font-semibold text-slate-900 mb-2">No Permit Required</h4>
                <ul class="space-y-1 text-slate-700 text-sm list-disc list-inside">
                  <li>Interior crack injection (cosmetic only)</li>
                  <li>Gutter and downspout improvements</li>
                  <li>Lot grading adjustments under 150mm</li>
                  <li>Dehumidifier installation</li>
                  <li>Landscaping changes for drainage</li>
                </ul>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold text-slate-900 mt-8 mb-4">Conservation Halton Regulated Areas</h3>

          <p>
            Conservation Halton regulates development and site alteration within environmentally sensitive areas under Ontario Regulation 162/06. In Burlington, regulated areas include: Spencer Creek and Sixteen Mile Creek floodplains and meander belts, areas within 15 meters of any watercourse or wetland, the Niagara Escarpment Development Control Area, and hazardous lands including steep slopes and unstable soils.
          </p>

          <p>
            Approximately 35-40% of Burlington properties fall within Conservation Halton regulated areas, though many homeowners don't realize it until they apply for building permits. The City of Burlington building permit application process includes Conservation Halton screening—if your property is in a regulated area, the City will refer your application to Conservation Halton for review, adding 4-6 weeks to approval timelines.
          </p>

          <p>
            Conservation Halton permits for waterproofing typically cost $850-$1,400 depending on project scope and whether technical studies (geotechnical reports, hydrological assessments) are required. Properties within creek floodplains usually need flood-proofing designs prepared by licensed engineers, adding $1,500-$3,000 to project costs. However, most routine waterproofing work outside of creek floodplains receives administrative approval without requiring detailed studies.
          </p>

          <p>
            Properties on or near the Niagara Escarpment may also fall under Niagara Escarpment Commission jurisdiction in addition to Conservation Halton. The escarpment Development Control Area in Burlington roughly follows the escarpment face from Mountainside through Headon Forest. Work in this zone requires Niagara Escarpment Development Permits, though routine waterproofing that doesn't alter natural features usually qualifies for exemptions.
          </p>

          <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold text-slate-900 mt-8 mb-4">Halton Region Basement Flooding Prevention Subsidy Program</h3>

          <p>
            Halton Region offers one of Ontario's most generous basement flooding prevention subsidy programs, providing up to $3,400 per property for eligible improvements. The program is administered through the City of Burlington but funded by Regional dollars, creating a seamless application process for Burlington homeowners.
          </p>

          <div class="bg-green-50 border-l-4 border-green-500 p-6 my-8 rounded-r-lg">
            <h3 class="font-bold text-lg text-slate-900 mb-2">Halton Region Basement Flooding Prevention Subsidies (2026)</h3>
            <ul class="space-y-3 text-slate-700">
              <li><strong>Backwater Valve Installation:</strong> Up to $1,250 subsidy (typically covers 60-80% of installation cost). Prevents sewage backup from municipal systems during heavy rainfall events.</li>
              <li><strong>Sump Pump Installation:</strong> Up to $1,250 subsidy for new sump pump systems, including basin, pump, discharge piping, and electrical connections. Properties without existing sumps prioritized.</li>
              <li><strong>Foundation Drainage Improvements:</strong> Up to $900 subsidy for perimeter drainage repairs, downspout disconnection and redirection, and lot grading improvements that direct water away from foundations.</li>
              <li><strong>Total Maximum Subsidy:</strong> $3,400 per property, covering multiple improvements in a single application or over multiple years (one application per flooding event).</li>
            </ul>
          </div>

          <p>
            Eligibility for Halton Region subsidies requires: property location in Burlington (or other Halton municipality), documented history of basement flooding or location in designated flood-risk area, work performed by licensed contractors with proper permits, and post-installation inspection to verify proper installation. Applications must be submitted before work begins—retroactive applications for completed work are not accepted.
          </p>

          <p>
            The application process involves: completing the Region's application form with property details and flooding history, obtaining quotes from licensed contractors for proposed work, submitting the application and receiving conditional approval before starting work, completing the work with proper permits and inspections, and submitting final invoices and inspection reports for subsidy payment.
          </p>

          <p>
            Processing times for subsidy applications average 4-6 weeks from submission to conditional approval. Payments are issued 3-4 weeks after final inspection approval. Burlington homeowners should factor these timelines into project planning—you'll need to pay contractors in full upon completion and wait for subsidy reimbursement.
          </p>

          <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold text-slate-900 mt-8 mb-4">Other Financial Assistance Programs</h3>

          <p>
            Beyond Halton Region subsidies, Burlington homeowners can access other financial assistance for waterproofing and flood prevention. The Canada Greener Homes Loan program provides up to $40,000 in interest-free loans for home improvements including flood resilience measures, though waterproofing specifically qualifies only when part of comprehensive energy efficiency retrofits.
          </p>

          <p>
            Property tax deferral programs through the City of Burlington allow seniors and low-income homeowners to defer property tax payments, freeing up cash flow for essential home repairs including waterproofing. Home Accessibility Tax Credit (federal) provides up to $1,500 annual tax credits for aging-in-place modifications, which can include basement improvements that prevent flooding-related safety hazards.
          </p>

          <p>
            Some home insurance providers offer premium discounts (5-10%) for properties with documented waterproofing systems and flood prevention measures. Ask your insurance broker about discounts available for backwater valve installation, sump pump systems with battery backup, and foundation waterproofing—annual savings of $80-$150 can offset system maintenance costs over time.
          </p>
